  glossary:[
    {term:"Block",def:"A container of validated transactions linked to the previous block via cryptographic hash. Contains: header (previous hash, Merkle root, timestamp, nonce) + body (transaction list)."},
    {term:"Hash (SHA-256)",def:"A cryptographic fingerprint — fixed-length output from any input. Deterministic, one-way, avalanche effect. Links blocks together: each block stores the previous block's hash."},
    {term:"Consensus Mechanism",def:"Protocol for network agreement on ledger state. PoW (Bitcoin): computational puzzle solving. PoS (Ethereum): staking cryptocurrency as collateral. Ensures all copies agree without central authority."},
    {term:"Smart Contract",def:"Self-executing code on a blockchain that runs automatically when conditions are met. Immutable once deployed. Enables DeFi, NFTs, DAOs. Written in Solidity (Ethereum) or Rust (Solana)."},
    {term:"Private Key / Public Key",def:"Cryptographic key pair. Private key (secret, 256-bit number) signs transactions and proves ownership. Public key (derived from private key) verifies signatures. Losing your private key = losing your funds permanently."},
    {term:"Mining / Staking",def:"Mining (PoW): using computing power to solve puzzles and add blocks — rewarded with cryptocurrency. Staking (PoS): locking cryptocurrency as collateral to validate blocks — rewarded with fees and new tokens."},
    {term:"DeFi",def:"Decentralized Finance — financial services (lending, trading, insurance) built as smart contracts on blockchains, operating without banks or intermediaries. ~$90B Total Value Locked."},
    {term:"NFT",def:"Non-Fungible Token — unique blockchain token representing ownership of a specific digital (or physical) item. Unlike fungible tokens (each BTC is identical), each NFT is unique."},
    {term:"Layer 2",def:"Scaling solutions processing transactions off the main blockchain (Layer 1) and periodically settling on L1 for security. Lightning Network (Bitcoin), Rollups (Ethereum). Enables thousands of TPS at low fees."},
    {term:"Gas",def:"Unit measuring computational work on Ethereum. Users pay gas fees (in ETH) proportional to transaction complexity. Gas Price varies with network demand — high congestion = expensive gas."},
  ],
  relatedTopics:["internet","cybersecurity","cloud"],
  childSummary:"Imagine a notebook that THOUSANDS of people all have identical copies of. When someone writes a new entry (like 'Alice paid Bob ₹500'), EVERYONE writes it in their copy at the same time. Each page has a special seal (hash) that's connected to the previous page's seal — like links in a chain. If ANYONE tries to secretly change an old entry, the seals break and everyone else's copies show the change — making cheating impossible! This magical tamper-proof shared notebook is called a blockchain. Bitcoin uses it to track money transfers, Ethereum uses it to run automatic programs (smart contracts), and it works without any bank or company in charge — just math and computers!",
